__Repurposing Drugs to Alleviate ER Stress-Induced Neurodegeneration in a Mouse Model of GM2 Gangliosidosis__

Our studies focus on repurposing FDA-approved drugs to treat GM2 gangliosidoses, such as Tay-Sachs and Sandhoff diseases. These are fatal lysosomal storage disorders characterized by a toxic accumulation of lipids that triggers severe endoplasmic reticulum (ER) stress and progressive neurodegeneration. To address this, we tested FDA-approved compounds to find a treatment capable of mitigating ER stress and preventing cell death. We identified 4-Phenylbutyric acid (4-PBA), a chemical chaperone, as the most promising lead candidate. When tested in a mouse model for Sandhoff disease, 4-PBA successfully shifted the cellular stress response away from apoptosis (cell death) and toward adaptive survival pathways. This intervention produced several major therapeutic benefits. It dramatically reduced cell death and preserved vulnerable motor neurons in the spinal cord. It maintained healthy skeletal muscle architecture, preventing muscle atrophy. The treatment significantly enhanced motor and neuromuscular function, maintained body weight, and extended the overall lifespan of the mice. Because 4-PBA is already FDA-approved and has an established safety profile, our study represents a highly promising, fast-track therapeutic strategy that could be rapidly advanced to clinical trials for patients with GM2 gangliosidoses.
